data.content:
Your test works, but `Assert.IsTrue` gives poor failure messages (just "Expected: True, Actual: False"). MSTest 3.x+ has specialized collection assertions with much better diagnostics:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Your original | Better alternative | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Shows "collection was empty" vs generic "was false" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Shows "expected 3, got 5" on failure |
| `Single()` + `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.ContainsSingle(filtered)` | Clearer intent, better failure message |

Other useful collection assertions:
```csharp
Assert.Contains(expectedItem, collection);
Assert.DoesNotContain(badItem, collection);
Assert.IsEmpty(collection);
```

These all require **MSTest 3.8+**. Check your package version if they don't resolve.
